{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"94794c79-0d4a-4057-b470-218f01d46822","content":"Here's how to collect a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n### 1. Exec into the container\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n### 2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present)\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n### 3. Find your process\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n### 4. Collect the trace\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### Copying the trace off the pod\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod-name>:<path-to-trace-file> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n### Alternative: `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, threadpool stats — useful to confirm the issue before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If `dotnet tool install` fails because the container lacks internet access, you can copy the tool in via `kubectl cp` or bake it into the container image.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3441504c-ceb7-405f-ba49-f96439b4cdf3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU usage. This is a knowledge/advice question, not a code task, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":407,"requestId":"6785:AFA09:AED55ED:BDC2DD9:69FD3B31"},"id":"c13f3767-376a-4764-aed1-2138d43b09ca","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:24:11.146Z","parentId":"28fd010c-e3d6-4219-aab0-1b93073f2f4f"}
